  "local_port": 48096,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some cool Java tricks?",
  "response": "Java, being a versatile and widely-used programming language, has several interesting tricks and features that can enhance your coding experience and productivity. Here are some cool Java tricks:\n\n1. **String Formatting with `String.format()`**:\n   This method allows you to format strings easily, similar to `printf` in C.\n\n   ```java\n   String name = \"Alice\";\n   int age = 30;\n   String formattedString = String.format(\"Name: %s, Age: %d\", name, age);\n   System.out.println(formattedString); // Output: Name: Alice, Age: 30\n   ```\n\n2. **Using `var` for Local Variable Type Inference (Java 10+)**:\n   This allows you to declare local variables without specifying the type explicitly.\n\n   ```java\n   var list = new ArrayList<String>();\n   list.add(\"Java\");\n   list.add(\"is\");\n   list.add(\"awesome\");\n   System.out.println(list); // Output: [Java, is, awesome]\n   ```\n\n3. **Diamond Operator (`<>`) for Generics (Java 7+)**:\n   Simplifies the instantiation of generic classes.\n\n   ```java\n   List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(); // No need to repeat <String>\n   list.add(\"Hello\");\n   System.out.println(list); // Output: [Hello]\n   ```\n\n4. **Try-With-Resources (Java 7+)**:\n   Automatically closes resources that implement `AutoCloseable`, reducing boilerplate code.\n\n   ```java\n   try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(\"file.txt\"))) {\n       String line;\n       while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {\n           System.out.println(line);\n       }\n   } catch (IOException e) {\n       e.printStackTrace();\n   }\n   ```\n\n5. **Method References and Lambda Expressions (Java 8+)**:\n   These features make your code more concise and readable.\n\n   ```java\n   // Using lambda expression\n   List<String> list = Arrays.asList(\"a\", \"b\", \"c\");\n   list.forEach(item -> System.out.println(item));\n\n   // Using method reference\n   list.forEach(System.out::println);\n   ```\n\n6. **Stream API (Java 8+)**:\n   Powerful for processing collections of objects.\n\n   ```java\n   List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);\n   int sum = numbers.stream()\n                    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)\n                    .mapToInt(Integer::intValue)\n                    .sum();\n   System.out.println(sum); // Output: 6 (sum of even numbers)\n   ```\n\n7. **Optional Class (Java 8+)**:\n   Helps to handle null values more effectively.\n\n   ```java\n   Optional<String> optional = Optional.ofNullable(null);\n   optional.ifPresent(System.out::println); // Nothing will be printed\n   System.out.println(optional.orElse(\"Default\")); // Output: Default\n   ```\n\n8. **Text Blocks (Java 15+)**:\n   Allows multi-line string literals, which is great for readability.\n\n   ```java\n   String html = \"\"\"\n                 <html>\n                     <body>\n                         <p>Hello, World!</p>\n                     </body>\n                 </html>\n                 \"\"\";\n   System.out.println(html);\n   ```\n\n9. **Records (Java 16+)**:\n   Simplifies the creation of classes that are little more than data holders.\n\n   ```java\n   record Person(String name, int age) {}\n\n   Person person = new Person(\"Bob\", 25);\n   System.out.println(person.name()); // Output: Bob\n   System.out.println(person.age());  // Output: 25\n   ```\n\n10. **Switch Expressions (Java 12+)**:\n    A more concise and expressive way to use switch statements.\n\n    ```java\n    int day = 2;\n    String dayType = switch (day) {\n        case 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 -> \"Weekday\";\n        case 6, 7 -> \"Weekend\";\n        default -> \"Invalid day\";\n    };\n    System.out.println(dayType); // Output: Weekday\n    ```\n\nThese tricks can make your Java programming more efficient and enjoyable. Remember to check the Java version you're using to ensure compatibility with these features.",
